message.content:
Explanation and reasoning

- The controller method handling POST /v1/posts is PostController::store. It returns a PostResource wrapping the newly created Post model instance:
  - return new PostResource(Post::create(...))
  - This means a successful response returns a JSON resource representation of the created Post.
- The request uses PostsRequest which declares validation rules:
  - title: required
  - content: required
  - posted_at: required|date (prepareForValidation parses posted_at into a Carbon date)
  - thumbnail_id: nullable|exists:media,id
  - author_id: required|exists:users,id plus custom rule CanBeAuthor
  - slug uniqueness rule
  - Validation failures in Laravel produce a 422 Unprocessable Entity JSON response with a message and errors object.
- The controller also calls $this->authorize('store', Post::class). Authorization failures in Laravel produce a 403 Forbidden JSON response with a message like "This action is unauthorized."
- From the Post Resource (App\Http\Resources\Post), the JSON representation includes fields:
  - id (integer), title (string), slug (string), content (string), posted_at (ISO8601 string), author_id (integer), comments_count (integer), thumbnail_url (string when present), thumb_thumbnail_url (string when present).
- Laravel JsonResource typically wraps single resources in a top-level "data" key (JsonResource default wrapping). The response schema below models that structure: top-level object with "data" containing the post resource object.

Based on the above, the responses included are:
- 200 — successful creation (returns the Post resource JSON)
- 403 — authorization failure (message)
- 422 — validation failure (message + errors map)

